Items.insert({name:"BLARNEY",category:"program",family:"collect",status:"unknown",description:"[[BLARNEY]] (\'\'\'US-984\'\'\' and \'\'\'US-984X\'\'\')is a communications surveillance program, started in 1978 and operated under [[FISA]]<ref name=fantastico1>{{cite news|url=http://g1.globo.com/fantastico/noticia/2013/09/nsa-documents-show-united-states-spied-brazilian-oil-giant.html|title=NSA Documents Show United States Spied Brazilian Oil Giant|date=September 8, 2013|accessdate=September 9, 2013}}</ref> <!--Really screengrabs in the attached video, they are exposed for only a few frames each-->.<ref name=\"wp_slides\">{{cite news | author = Staff | url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/special/politics/prism-collection-documents/ | date = June 6, 2013 |title=NSA Slides Explain the PRISM Data-Collection Program |work=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate = September 9, 2013}}</ref> The collection takes place at top-level telecommunications facilities within the United States, choke points through which most traffic will flow, including wireless. This type of surveillance is referred to as \"Upstream Collection.\" It was first brought to public view in a [[PRISM]] slide revealed by [[Edward Snowden]].<ref name=\"wp_slides\"/> <!-- It retains the content of emails, and phone calls made with Internet technology (i.e., [[VoIP]]) made within the United States. [May not be specific enough]--> Among the facilities associated with BLARNEY are [[AT&amp;T]]\'s [[Room 641A]] in [[San Francisco]], California, revealed in 2006 by [[Mark Klein]], and another in [[New Jersey]]. Like its counterparts, BLARNEY was expanded after the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name=wsj1>{{cite news|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887324108204579022874091732470.html|title=New Details Show Broader NSA Surveillance Reach |authors=Siobhan Gorman and Jennifer Valentio-DeVries|date=August 20, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref>Information collected from BLARNEY is shared with many agencies in the United States, including the CIA, NSA, FBI and DOJ, it is also shared with the [[Five Eyes]] and [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization|NATO]]. A number of private companies also have access.<ref name=fantastico1/>",relatedItems:[""],links:[]});
